JonWallsten:
If you use jQuery:
What if you listen to the scroll event and check the sticky item's position(). Then compare it to the position's top/bottom value, if they match, it should be in sticky mode, and you can add the class, otherwise remove it. (It won't be exactly this simple but you get the point)
Edit: I did this in a project, but only for top.
Basically like this. This depens on offset though, so the element cannot be bound to a container that is not the full size of the window. The idea to a solution in the top is more robust.
if( Math.floor($('menu').offset().top) == $(window).scrollTop() || Math.floor($('menu').offset().top) == 0 ) {
   $('menu').addClass('sticky');
} else {
  $('menu').removeClass('sticky');
}
